The paper deals with the problem of selecting a subset of rules based on their operational behavior on available data. This problem is relevant in several applications, including data transformation and entity resolution, which are typically associated with the sub-categories of artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and databases (cs.DB). The paper also uses complexity-theoretic tools to analyze the computational hardness and approximability of the rule selection problem, which are typical of the sub-categories of algorithms and complexity (cs.CC) and data structures (cs.DS). Finally, the paper considers bi-objective and bi-level optimization versions of the rule selection problem, which are related to the sub-category of machine learning (cs.LG).
